\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Our paper is an invitation to travel in an unexpected way: diving through the Linked Open Data cloud, with the help of Alex, a robot. This robot uses SPARQL endpoint to jump from one \'91set\'92 of RDF triples to another. Before starting this exploration\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
, we would like to first introduce you to Henry Carton de Wiart, a famous Belgian personality. Part of a large noble family, he has been minister several times, Prime Minister, president of many councils and organisations, and a lawyer and a writer as well. As you may know, the Belgian city Li\'e8ge owes its name to one of his books, La Cit\'e9 ardente. Moreover, he has been honored by several awards and was in contact with many well-known personalities, from the poet Verlaine to the President Wilson. Still, it already appears that his life contains sufficient information to be used as a case study to observe how linked open data documents his life.\
\
While many studies about Linked Open Data adopt distant approaches based on methods such as data mining or network analysis, they therefore tend to analyse the data quality of cultural heritage linked data only through the prism of quantitative and comparative analysis [inclure un exemple typique pour appuyer le propos ?], without taking individual items one by one. In this case-study, we opt for a close-reading approach focusing on a single individuality and its data quality, in order to analysis how the triple structure succeeds to capture biographical data, compare with more traditional authority files. The paper is structured as follows: \'85\'85..\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \

\b Continuum\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Linked open data fits in a landscape of pre-existing resources, going from unstructured data to very structured data. At one end are situated less structured data, like the national biography of Henry Carton de Wiart, 8 sheets of well-written text, which have been digitised end published online in a PDF version [cf. r\'e9f\'e9rence : http://www.academieroyale.be/Academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2102.pdf, p. 86-94]. At the other end, stand the most structured data, which correspond to Linked Data, such as the Wikidata item attributed to Henry [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q14990"}}{\fldrslt https://wikidata.org/wiki/Q14990}}], the Viaf entity [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://viaf.org/viaf/24623115/"}}{\fldrslt https://viaf.org/viaf/24623115/}}] or the french DBpedia page [http://fr.dbpedia.org/page/Henry_Carton_de_Wiart]. In between, are established more isolated structured data like RDF triples from several archives and libraries [e.g. Data.bnf.fr : {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://data.bnf.fr/12062835/henry_carton_de_wiart/"}}{\fldrslt http://data.bnf.fr/12062835/henry_carton_de_wiart/}}], archival descriptions in XML [e.g. the EAC-cpf file from the State Archives of Belgium: the https://search.arch.be/eac/xml/eac-BE-A0500_007556_FRE.xml] or Wikipedia pages [e.g. the english version: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Carton_de_Wiart"}}{\fldrslt https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Carton_de_Wiart}}]. \
While the most structured resources display facts (such as a birth date or death date) very clearly, in a machine-readable format, we can wonder if they provide as many details as a more classical format type, such as the national biography: do they mention its Hennuy\'e8res origins, his correspondence with an apostolic vicar living in Brazzaville, or that day in August 1914 when the Belgian king asked him to lead an extraordinary mission to the United States? Through this case study, we aim to test and confront these various sources and to observe to what extent they are consistent and complementary. \
\
